Analects 2.4 

 
 

 

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

 
The first word, wú (吾), is Modern Chinese wǒ. Ér (而), which occurs in every line above with the same 
function, is a Classical Chinese conjunction which can sometimes be translated ‘and’, but in these contexts 
requires something more explicit such as ‘having done so’, ‘on doing so’, ‘on reaching [the age of 30]’, etc. 
 
“The Master said: At fifteen I was determined on learning, at thirty I was established, at forty I had no 
doubts, at fifty I understood the commands of Heaven, at sixty my ears were obedient, at seventy I may 
follow what my heart desires without transgressing the limits.” Translation from E. Bruce Brooks and A. 
Taeko Brooks, The Original Analects: Sayings of Confucius and His Successors [p. 110]. 
 
 

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

