12.4  Kinship   
There are two types of kinterms, those used in direct address (‘Hi, Dad’), and those used 
to refer to the relationship (‘father’). In Chinese, a child may address her grandfather on 
her father’s side (her zǔfù) as yéye, her grandfather on her mother’s side (her wàigōng or 
wài zǔfù), as gōnggong. Typically, the address forms show wide variation in Chinese, as 
they do in English (eg for ‘grandmother’, grandma, granny, gran, mawmaw, etc.) So 
while the relationships mentioned in the passage below are all significant in the Chinese 
kinship system, the particular terms cited may vary from region to region. You might 
compare the usage here with that of your Chinese friends.  
 

