12.9  Confrontation (2) 
While you are still coming to grips with basic conversational material, it is appropriate to 
try to speak a standard form of the language, and adopt a fairly formal level of usage. 
However, if you live in a Chinese setting, you will quickly realize that the Mandarin that 
you hear on the street (rather than in an institutional setting) is likely to be quite regional 
in its usage, and informal – larded with colorful language, slang, obscenities and obscure 
references. The conversation below, though still rather idealized compared to real life, 
provides a glimpse of what to observe. But first, a digression to introduce some language 
of mild abuse. 
 
